    <h1>ClientFlow-CRM <br>(Rafiullah Daniyal Usman)</h1>
    <p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Semester Project Documentation</strong></p>

    <h2>1. Introduction &amp; Overall Functionality</h2>
    <p>ClientFlow-CRM is a modern, single-page web application designed for small businesses to manage their daily operations. The primary goal of this project is to centralize business data so that employees and administrators can easily track who their customers are, who owes them money, and what tasks need to be completed.</p>
    
    <p><strong>Core Functionalities:</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Authentication:</strong> Secure login and registration. Includes "Admin" and "Employee" roles to restrict who can see certain data.</li>
        <li><strong>Customer Management:</strong> Create, read, update, and delete (CRUD) customer profiles.</li>
        <li><strong>Lead Tracking:</strong> Track potential clients ("Leads") and monitor their estimated financial value.</li>
        <li><strong>Invoicing &amp; Payments:</strong> Generate invoices for customers and log payments against those invoices.</li>
        <li><strong>Task &amp; Appointment Scheduling:</strong> Assign daily tasks to employees and schedule upcoming meetings.</li>
        <li><strong>Real-Time Dashboard:</strong> A visual dashboard showing total revenue, active customers, and a live weather widget.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>2. Setup Instructions</h2>
    <p>Follow these simple steps to run the project on your local machine:</p>
    
    <div class="highlight">
        <h3>Step A: Setup the Database</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>Open <strong>SQL Server Management Studio (SSMS)</strong>.</li>
            <li>Create a brand new, empty database and name it <strong>ClientFlowCRM</strong>.</li>
            <li>Open the provided <code>db_setup.sql</code> file in SSMS.</li>
            <li>Execute the script. This will instantly create all the necessary tables (Customers, Invoices, AspNetUsers, etc.) without any complex migrations.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Step B: Run the Application</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>Open the solution file (<code>ClientFlowCRM.slnx</code>) in Visual Studio 2022.</li>
            <li>Click the green <strong>"Play/Run"</strong> button at the top (or run <code>dotnet run</code> in the terminal).</li>
            <li>The website will launch in your browser.</li>
            <li>Sign in using the default Admin account:<br>
                <strong>Email:</strong> admin@ClientFlowCRM.com<br>
                <strong>Password:</strong> Admin@123
            </li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <h2>3. Architecture Breakdown (How it Works)</h2>
    <p>The project uses a <strong>Blazor Server</strong> architecture built on .NET 10. This means everything (the user interface, the database connection, and the business logic) lives securely in one single project (<code>ClientFlowCRM.Server</code>). Here is what each folder does in the easiest words possible:</p>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Models:</strong> These are simple C# classes that represent real-world objects. For example, <code>Customer.cs</code> has properties for FirstName, LastName, and Email. These perfectly match the columns in the SQL database.</li>
        <li><strong>Data (ApplicationDbContext):</strong> This is the bridge between the C# code and the SQL Server. Entity Framework Core uses this bridge to save and retrieve Models from the database without writing raw SQL queries.</li>
        <li><strong>DTOs (Data Transfer Objects):</strong> These are lightweight versions of Models. Instead of sending the entire heavy database Model to the screen, we pack only the necessary information into a DTO (like putting it in a lightweight shipping box) to make the app run faster.</li>
        <li><strong>Controllers:</strong> These are the "traffic cops" of the application (API endpoints). When the user wants to delete a customer, the Controller receives that request, checks if it's safe to do so, tells the Database to delete it, and sends a "Success" message back.</li>
        <li><strong>Services:</strong> This is where the heavy lifting happens. Instead of writing complex logic inside the visual pages, the UI asks a Service (like <code>CustomerService.cs</code>) to fetch data from the Controllers.</li>
        <li><strong>Pages (UI):</strong> These are the visual screens you see in the browser (ending in <code>.razor</code>). They combine HTML, CSS, and C# code. For example, <code>Customers.razor</code> displays the HTML table and uses a C# loop to draw a new row for every customer.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>4. Example Data Flow (Clicking "Delete Customer")</h2>
    <p>To understand how the project works, imagine you click the "Delete" button on a Customer:</p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>The UI (Customers.razor):</strong> You click the button. The Razor page catches the click and triggers a C# function called <code>DeleteCustomer()</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>The Service (CustomerService.cs):</strong> The UI asks the CustomerService to handle the request. The Service sends an HTTP DELETE request across the network to the API.</li>
        <li><strong>The Controller (CustomersController.cs):</strong> The Controller intercepts this request. It first checks if the Customer has any active Invoices. If they do, it immediately rejects the request to prevent database crashes.</li>
        <li><strong>The Database (DbContext):</strong> If there are no invoices, the Controller tells Entity Framework to find the Customer in the SQL database and remove them.</li>
        <li><strong>The Result:</strong> The Controller sends a "Success" signal back to the Service, which tells the UI to pop up a green "Deleted Successfully" notification and refresh the table.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>5. Advanced Components</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Authentication (CustomAuthStateProvider.cs):</strong> This acts as a digital bouncer. When you log in, it gives you a digital wristband (a JWT Token). Every time you try to view a page, it checks your wristband to see if you are an "Admin" or an "Employee".</li>
        <li><strong>WeatherWidget (WeatherService.cs):</strong> This component reaches out to a completely external website (OpenWeatherMap) using an API Key, downloads the live weather data for the user's city, and draws it on the Dashboard.</li>
    </ul>

